Like most other reported CDs, the synthesized N-CDs also have a concentration-dependent emission behavior. As shown in Fig. 3

                        (a), the emission peak of N-CDs shifts from 517 to 572 nm under the optimal excitation wavelength when the N-CDs concentration varies from 0.01 to 1.87 mg/mL. Furthermore, the relationship between the emission characteristic and the concentration of N-CDs is shown in Fig. 3
                        (b). As the concentration increases, the fluorescence intensity increases initially and then decreases, while the emission wavelength of N-CDs gradually increases. Concomitantly, the color of the N-CDs solution gradually darkens, and the fluorescence images change from cyan to orange under a UV lamp (
                           Fig. S3
                        ). According to the absorption spectra of N-CDs (
                           Fig. S4
                        ), the Tauc plots of (αhυ)2
                         verses hυ are exhibited to obtain the optical band gaps (Eg
                        ). It is observed that the energy gap gradually reduces from 2.66 to 2.53 eV as the concentration increases (Fig. 3
                        (c)), which agrees well with the redshift of emission wavelength. Notably, a large overlap is observed between the absorption and emission spectra of N-CDs (
                           Fig. S5
                        ), which may be ascribed to the FRET or re-absorption that always occurs in a small interparticle distance less than Förster distance (R0
                        ) [33]. At the high concentration, the uniform dispersion of N-CDs becomes unstable due to the extremely short distance and the high-energy state. Thus N-CDs tend to aggregate together to remain stable in solution. Therefore, the short wavelength part of emission that overlaps the absorption (400–500 nm) is weakened due to the energy transfer. In contrast, the long part is less attenuated than the short part, resulting in a significant red shift with the concentration increasing [34–36].
